# Version Control — Complete Professional Notes

---

## 1. What Is Version Control?

**Version control** (also called source control or revision control) is a system that records every change made to files over time, so you can recall specific versions later, understand who changed what and why, and collaborate with a team without overwriting each other's work.

### Why It Exists — The Problem It Solves

Without version control, teams fall into a set of predictable traps:

- Files named `report_final_v2_REAL_v3_FIXED.docx`
- Two people editing the same file simultaneously — one overwrites the other
- No record of why a change was made, or who made it
- No way to undo a mistake once the file is saved
- Fear of experimenting, because there is nothing to fall back on

Version control eliminates every one of these problems.

### Core Benefits

| Benefit | What It Means in Practice |
|--------|--------------------------|
| **Full history** | Every saved state of the project is accessible — revert any file to any point |
| **Collaboration** | Multiple developers work on the same codebase without blocking each other |
| **Accountability** | Every change is stamped with who made it, when, and why |
| **Experimentation** | Try new ideas in isolation; discard them with zero cost if they fail |
| **Disaster recovery** | Even if your machine fails, the full project history lives on the server |

---

## 2. Types of Version Control Systems

### 2a. Local Version Control

Tracks changes only on a single machine using a simple database. No collaboration, no remote backup.

**Example:** RCS (Revision Control System — 1980s)

**Limitation:** Cannot support teams; the history exists on one computer only.

---

### 2b. Centralized Version Control (CVCS)

A single central server holds all versioned files. Developers check out files from that server.

**Examples:** CVS, Subversion (SVN), Perforce

**Pros:**
- Simple mental model — one truth, one server
- Fine-grained access control at the file level

**Cons:**
- Single point of failure — if the server goes down, nobody can collaborate or save versions
- Requires network access to commit
- Slow on large projects

---

### 2c. Distributed Version Control (DVCS)

Every developer has a **complete copy** of the full repository history on their local machine — not just a snapshot of the current state.

**Examples:** **Git**, Mercurial, Bazaar

**Pros:**
- No single point of failure — every clone is a full backup
- Work offline; commit without network access
- Fast operations — most are local
- Multiple workflows become possible (forks, feature branches, etc.)

**Cons:**
- Slightly more complex mental model for beginners
- Larger initial clone size (full history downloaded)

> **Git is a DVCS.** This is the dominant model in professional software development today.

