## 3. Git — The Industry Standard

### What Is Git?

Git is a **free, open-source distributed version control system** created by Linus Torvalds in 2005 to manage the Linux kernel source code. It is now used by virtually every professional software team in the world.

**Key characteristics:**
- Distributed — every developer has the full history
- Fast — nearly all operations are local
- Branching is cheap and instant
- Data integrity — every snapshot is identified by a cryptographic hash (SHA-1)
- Non-destructive by design — it is very hard to permanently lose committed data

---

## 4. Core Git Concepts

Understanding these concepts is essential before running any commands.

### 4a. Repository (Repo)

A **repository** is the project folder that Git is tracking. It contains your files plus a hidden `.git/` directory which is Git's internal database — storing every version of every file ever committed.

```
my-project/
├── .git/          ← Git's database (do not touch manually)
├── src/
├── README.md
└── package.json
```

> If you delete `.git/`, you lose all history but keep your files.

---

### 4b. Working Directory

The **working directory** is what you see in your file system — the actual files you edit. Changes here are "unstaged" until you explicitly add them.

---

### 4c. Staging Area (Index)

The **staging area** is a preparation zone between your working files and the next commit. You select *which* changes to include in your next commit.

Think of it as packing a suitcase: you choose what goes in before you zip it up (commit).

```
Working Directory  →  git add  →  Staging Area  →  git commit  →  Repository
```

---

### 4d. Commit

A **commit** is a permanent, named snapshot of your project at a specific moment. Each commit contains:

- A unique SHA-1 identifier (e.g. `a3f9c12`)
- The author's name and email
- A timestamp
- A message describing the change
- A pointer to its parent commit(s)

Commits form a chain — the **commit history** — which you can navigate, search, and revert at any time.

---

### 4e. Branch

A **branch** is a lightweight, movable pointer to a specific commit. Branches let you develop features or fixes in isolation from the main codebase.

- **`main`** (or `master`) — the stable, production-ready line of development
- **Feature branches** — isolated branches for individual features or bug fixes

---

### 4f. Remote

A **remote** is a version of your repository hosted on another server (e.g. GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket). Remotes allow team members to share commits.

The default remote name is `origin`.

---

### 4g. HEAD

`HEAD` is a special pointer that tells Git which commit you are currently "on." It normally points to the tip of your current branch.

