## 6. Essential Git Commands

### Initial Setup (Run Once)

```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
git config --global core.editor "code --wait"   # Set VS Code as default editor
```

---

### Starting a Repository

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git init` | Initialise a new Git repo in the current folder |
| `git clone <url>` | Download a full copy of an existing remote repo (including all history) |

```bash
# Example: Clone a GitHub repo
git clone https://github.com/username/project.git
```

---

### Checking Status & History

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git status` | Show which files are modified, staged, or untracked |
| `git log` | Full commit history with author, date, and message |
| `git log --oneline` | Compact one-line-per-commit view |
| `git log --oneline --graph` | ASCII branch graph in the terminal |
| `git diff` | Show unstaged changes line by line |
| `git diff --staged` | Show staged changes (what will be committed) |
| `git show <hash>` | Show the full detail of a specific commit |

---

### Staging & Committing

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git add .` | Stage all changes in the current directory |
| `git add <file>` | Stage a specific file |
| `git add -p` | Interactively stage parts of files (hunk by hunk) |
| `git commit -m "message"` | Commit staged changes with an inline message |
| `git commit` | Open the editor to write a multi-line commit message |
| `git commit --amend` | Edit the most recent commit (message or content) |

---

### Pushing & Pulling

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git push` | Upload local commits to the remote |
| `git push -u origin main` | First push — sets tracking so future `git push` works alone |
| `git pull` | Fetch + merge remote changes into your current branch |
| `git fetch` | Download remote changes WITHOUT merging (safe to inspect first) |
| `git remote -v` | List configured remote URLs |
| `git remote add origin <url>` | Connect a local repo to a remote |

---

### Branching

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git branch` | List all local branches |
| `git branch -a` | List all branches (local + remote) |
| `git branch <name>` | Create a new branch (stay on current branch) |
| `git checkout <branch>` | Switch to a branch |
| `git checkout -b <name>` | Create AND switch to a new branch (shortcut) |
| `git switch <branch>` | Modern alternative to `git checkout` for switching |
| `git switch -c <name>` | Modern alternative: create and switch |
| `git branch -d <name>` | Delete a branch (safe — only if fully merged) |
| `git branch -D <name>` | Force delete a branch (even if not merged) |

---

### Merging

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git merge <branch>` | Merge the named branch into your current branch |
| `git merge --no-ff <branch>` | Force a merge commit even if fast-forward is possible |
| `git merge --abort` | Cancel a merge mid-conflict |

**Types of merge:**

- **Fast-forward merge** — No diverging work; Git simply moves the branch pointer forward. No merge commit is created.
- **3-way merge** — Both branches have diverged; Git creates a merge commit combining the two histories.

---

### Undoing Changes

| Command | What It Does | Safe? |
|---------|-------------|-------|
| `git revert <hash>` | Creates a new commit that undoes the specified commit | ✅ Yes — keeps history |
| `git reset HEAD <file>` | Unstage a file (keep changes in working dir) | ✅ Yes |
| `git checkout -- <file>` | Discard working directory changes (irreversible) | ⚠️ Destructive |
| `git reset --soft HEAD~1` | Undo last commit, keep changes staged | ⚠️ Rewrites history |
| `git reset --hard HEAD~1` | Undo last commit AND discard changes entirely | ❌ Dangerous |

> **Rule of thumb:** Use `git revert` on shared branches. Use `git reset` only on your own local/private branch.

---

### Stashing

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git stash` | Temporarily shelve uncommitted changes (clean working dir) |
| `git stash pop` | Restore the most recent stash and remove it from the stash list |
| `git stash list` | Show all stashed states |
| `git stash apply stash@{2}` | Apply a specific stash without removing it |
| `git stash drop stash@{0}` | Delete a specific stash |

**Use case:** You are mid-feature and need to pull in hotfix changes without committing unfinished work.

---

### Tagging

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git tag v1.0.0` | Create a lightweight tag on the current commit |
| `git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "Release 1.0.0"` | Create an annotated tag with a message |
| `git push origin v1.0.0` | Push a specific tag to the remote |
| `git push origin --tags` | Push all tags |

---

### Advanced / Power Commands

| Command | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git rebase <branch>` | Move your branch's commits on top of another branch (rewrites history) |
| `git cherry-pick <hash>` | Apply a specific commit from another branch onto the current branch |
| `git bisect start` | Begin a binary search to find the commit that introduced a bug |
| `git blame <file>` | Show who last modified each line of a file, and when |
| `git reflog` | Log of everything HEAD has pointed to — your safety net for lost commits |
| `git clean -fd` | Remove untracked files and directories |

