## 7. Branching Strategies

### 7a. Feature Branching (Most Common)

Every new feature or bug fix gets its own branch. When complete and reviewed, it is merged to `main`.

```
main
 ├── feature/user-auth
 ├── feature/payment-gateway
 └── bugfix/login-null-pointer
```

---

### 7b. Gitflow

A formal model with defined branch types. Best for products with scheduled releases.

| Branch | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `main` | Production code only |
| `develop` | Integration branch for completed features |
| `feature/*` | New features (branch from `develop`) |
| `release/*` | Release preparation (branch from `develop`) |
| `hotfix/*` | Emergency production fixes (branch from `main`) |

---

### 7c. Trunk-Based Development

All developers commit to `main` (the "trunk") directly or via very short-lived branches (less than a day). Relies on feature flags to hide unfinished work.

Best for: Teams with strong automated testing and CI/CD pipelines.

