## 13. Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| **Repository** | A project folder tracked by Git, including all history |
| **Commit** | A permanent snapshot of staged changes at a point in time |
| **Branch** | A named pointer to a series of commits; enables parallel development |
| **HEAD** | Pointer to the commit you are currently working from |
| **Remote** | A copy of the repo hosted on a server (e.g. GitHub) |
| **Origin** | The default name for the primary remote |
| **Clone** | A full local copy of a remote repository |
| **Staging Area** | The intermediate zone where changes are prepared before committing |
| **Merge** | Combining two branches into one |
| **Rebase** | Moving a branch's base commit to another point (rewrites history) |
| **Fast-forward** | A merge where no new merge commit is created — the pointer simply moves |
| **Conflict** | Occurs when two branches change the same lines; must be resolved manually |
| **Pull Request** | A request (on GitHub) to merge a branch into another, enabling code review |
| **Stash** | A temporary store for uncommitted changes |
| **Tag** | A permanent label for a specific commit — used for releases |
| **gitignore** | A file listing paths Git should never track |
| **SHA-1** | The cryptographic hash used to uniquely identify each commit |

